{{nihongo foot|'''''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'''''|夢幻戦士ヴァリス|Mugen Senshi: Varisu|lit. "Dream Soldier: Valis"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 1986 [[Action game|action]]-[[Platform game|platform]] [[video game]] originally developed by [[Wolf Team]] and published by [[Telenet Japan]] for the [[MSX]], [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]], [[X1 (computer)|X1]], [[FM-7]], and [[PC-9800 series|PC-9801]] home computers. It is the first entry in the ''[[Valis (video game series)|Valis]]'' series.  It stars Yuko Asou, a Japanese teenage schoolgirl chosen as the Valis warrior and wielder of the mystical Valis sword to protect the Earth, the land of spirits, and the dream world Vecanti from demon lord Rogles. Throughout the journey, the player explores and search for [[Item (gaming)|item]]s and [[power-up]]s, while fighting enemies and defeating [[Boss (video gaming)|bosses]] to increase Yuko's attributes.

Programmers Masahiro Akishino and Osamu Ikegame began planning on a side-scrolling action game featuring a customed delinquent heroine, an idea originated from ''[[Sukeban Deka]]'' to compete in a contest sponsored by Japanese computer magazine ''LOGiN'', being kept secret within Telenet until they approved development to continue when the company learned of its existence. After a Telenet superior expressed disliking towards its graphics, writer Hiroki Hayashi was ordered to take action and fix it, leading to the conception of ''Valis''. Akishino and Hayashi used Ikegame's work as basis to introduce their own story and character ideas, which were based on an unfinished personal novel Hayashi wrote prior to the game's production.

''Valis'' sold well and was listed as one of the best-selling games in 1987 rankings. An almost completely reworked version was also released for the [[Family Computer]], followed by remakes for the [[Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]] and [[PC Engine Super CD-ROM²]], and a version for [[mobile phone]]s as well. The game was supplemented with [[manga]] adaptations, an anime short by [[Sunrise (company)|Sunrise]], albums from [[King Records (Japan)|King Records]] and [[Wave Master]],  and [[doujinshi]] books. Critical reception has varied depending on the version; the original MSX version garnered mixed reviews while the Genesis remake carried average sentiments, however the enhanced PC Engine remake was received more favorably. It was followed by ''[[Valis II]]'' (1989).

== Gameplay and premise ==
[[File:MSX Valis - The Fantasm Soldier (Mugen Senshi - Varisu).png|frame|left|Gameplay screenshot of the [[MSX]] version]]
''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'' is an action-platform game starring Yuko Asou,{{efn|{{nihongo|麻生 優子|Asou Yūko}}}} a Japanese schoolgirl teenager who is fated to protect three different realms – the Earth, the land of spirits, and the dream world Vecanti. The demon lord Rogles{{efn|{{nihongo|ログレス|Roguresu}}}} extinguishes a light, which acts as a source of power for the inhabitants of Vecanti. In a desperate plea for salvation, the queen of Vecanti, Valia,{{efn|{{nihongo|ヴァリア|Varia}}}} reaches out for a brave soul who can help them in their time of despair, with Yuko being the one who answers the call. Yuko is magically summoned into becoming the Valis warrior by wielding the titular sword to liberate Vecanti from the evil of Rogles. Yuko's classmate, Reiko Kirishima,{{efn|{{nihongo||桐島 麗子|Kirishima Reiko}}}} is brainwashed by Rogles into helping him and destroy Yuko.<ref name="ValisHG101"/><ref name="VTFSum">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/FantasmSoldierValis1986TelenetJapanJP|title=夢幻戦士ヴァリス|date=1986|publisher=[[Telenet Japan]]|edition=Japanese|type=取扱説明書}}</ref>

Gameplay varies depending on the platform, but each version retains the same basic plot; in the original [[MSX]], [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] and [[X1 (computer)|X1]] versions, as well as the [[FM-7]] and [[PC-9800 series|PC-9801]] ports, ''Valis'' is a side-scrolling game where the player controls Yuko to fight through each level's enemies while jumping across ledges, exploring and searching for [[Item (gaming)|item]]s and [[power-up]]s, before confronting a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] at the end of each level to increase Yuko's maximum [[Health (game terminology)|health]] and attributes. At certain points in the game, gameplay pauses, and cinematic [[cutscene]]s play regarding the game's plot.<ref name="ValisHG101"/><ref name="VTFSum"/> The [[Family Computer]] version differs considerably from the other versions, being more akin to a side-scrolling [[action role-playing game]]. It is a more difficult game due to its larger maze-style levels with multiple paths, and a lack of a password or save feature.<ref name="ValisHG101"/>

The [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive/Genesis]] remake exhibits a gameplay system more similar to later games in the ''[[Valis (video game series)|Valis]]'' series, particularly ''[[Valis III]]''; the [[d-pad]] moves the main character and three buttons allow Yuko to perform three actions: sliding, jumping, and swinging her sword, which can be upgraded three times. The player can also use magic spells, gaining them after defeating bosses.<ref name="ValisHG101"/> The [[PC Engine Super CD-ROM²]] remake features changes to the gameplay system (e.g. single high jumps instead of two-phase jumps, a sliding move damaging enemies) and voiced cutscenes.<ref name="ValisHG101"/> The [[mobile phone]] version further added new stages and alternate costumes.

== Development ==
[[File:Shoujo Furyou Densetsu character art.jpg|thumb|right|Character artwork by Hiroki Hayashi of the unnamed main protagonist from ''Shoujo Furyou Densetsu'', before it was morphed into ''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier''.]]
''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'' was developed over the course of half a year by [[Wolf Team]], an internal gaming subsidiary of [[Telenet Japan]] founded in 1986.<ref name="ValisHG101"/><ref name="VTFSum"/><ref name="GSW"/><ref name="GemuShoku">{{cite book|last=Shigehara|first=Moriyuki|script-title=ja:山本 雅康|title=ゲーム職人 第1集 だから日本のゲームは面白い|publisher=Micro Magazine|date=October 30, 2007|pages=1–157|language=ja|isbn=978-4896372670}} ([https://shmuplations.com/valis/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220219032131/https://shmuplations.com/valis/|date=2022-02-19}}).</ref> It was co-produced by conceptual designer Hiroki Hayashi and Yukio Mitsuhashi, both of whom acted as co-designers and co-scenario writters as well.<ref name="VTFSum"/><ref name="VTFSmsx">{{cite video game|title=夢幻戦士ヴァリス|developer=[[Wolf Team]]|publisher=[[Telenet Japan]]|date=November 26, 1986|platform=[[MSX]]|level=[[Staff roll]]|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="VTFSpc88">{{cite video game|title=夢幻戦士ヴァリス|developer=[[Wolf Team]]|publisher=[[Telenet Japan]]|date=December 1986|platform=[[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]]|level=[[Staff roll]]|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="RM5">{{cite magazine|last=Romero|first=Francisco|url=https://archive.org/details/RetroManiac-Magazine-5/page/n101/mode/2up|title=25 Especial Aniversario: Valis|magazine=RetroManiac Magazine|issue=5|publisher=RetroManiac|date=September 2011|pages=102–111|language=es}}</ref> Masahiro Akishino provided additional scenario support and served as programmer of the [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] version.<ref name="VTFSum"/><ref name="VTFSpc88"/><ref name="Technopolisv5i52">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/technopolis-volume-52-november-1986/page/105/mode/1up|title=HOT ACCESS To Techno Man 42回|magazine=[[:ja:テクノポリス (雑誌)|Technopolis]]|volume=5|issue=52|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=November 1986|pages=105–108|language=ja}}</ref> Former [[Compile (company)|Compile]] staffer Tomoki Anazawa and Masayasu Yamamoto served as main programmers for the [[MSX]] and [[X1 (computer)|X1]] versions respectively.<ref name="VTFSum"/><ref name="GemuShoku"/><ref name="VTFSmsx"/><ref name="RM5"/> Hayashi also acted as art director, with Daisuke Kiyasu, Hiroshi Toriumi, Makoto Takahashi, Mitsuru Takahashi, Shinichi Shiino, and Tsuyoshi Tanaka being responsible for the graphics.<ref name="VTFSum"/><ref name="GemuShoku"/><ref name="VTFSmsx"/><ref name="VTFSpc88"/> The music was composed by Shinobu Ogawa.<ref name="VTFSmsx"/><ref name="VTFSpc88"/><ref name="Technopolisv5i52"/><ref name="VGMO"/>

Akishino and programmer Osamu Ikegame started planning on a project tentatively titled ''Shoujo Furyou Densetsu'',{{efn|{{nihongo|少女不良伝説|Shōjo Furyō Densetsu}}}} a side-scrolling action game featuring a customed delinquent heroine, who would have served as a vehicle to showcase the action.<ref name="GemuShoku"/><ref name="GRTTb2">{{cite web|last=Hayashi|first=Hiroki|url=http://park3.wakwak.com/~garakutaten/data/valis/valis_data/valis_tanjyou_hiwa.htm|script-title=ja:『夢幻戦士ヴァリス』製作資料 - ヴァリス誕生秘話: 【 「ヴァリス」の開発母体となった幻のゲーム『少女不良伝説』…ヴァリス誕生秘話 】 - 『夢幻戦士ヴァリス』誕生秘話|work=我楽多展 - GA・RAKU・TA・TEN|date=2006|access-date=2022-04-09|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060827022233/http://park3.wakwak.com/~garakutaten/data/valis/valis_data/valis_tanjyou_hiwa.htm|archive-date=2006-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref> The idea originated from ''[[Sukeban Deka]]'', particularly the [[live-action]] television adaptation, as both Akishino and Ikegame were fans of the series.<ref name="GemuShoku"/><ref name="GRTTb2"/> The project was made as an entry for "Program Olympics", a contest sponsored by Japanese computer magazine ''LOGiN'' where game developers created software to compete.<ref name="GRTTb2"/><ref name="LOGiNv4i10">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/logi-n-october-1985/page/n85/mode/2up|title=「プログラムオリンピック2」|magazine=[[:ja:ログイン (雑誌)|LOGiN]]|volume=4|issue=10|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=October 1985|pages=92–119|lang=ja}}</ref> The game was kept secret within Telenet, but when the company learned of its existence, they approved development to continue.<ref name="GRTTb2"/>

Yamamoto was set to work on the game ''Final Zone Wolf'', before being switched to ''Shoujo Furyou Densetsu'' due to staff shortage.<ref name="GemuShoku"/> Hayashi joined the staff after development of ''Final Zone Wolf'' had finished, helping with making various settings and drawing character artwork of the unnamed main protagonist.<ref name="GRTTb2"/> One day, a Telenet superior came to the development room to inspect the situation and expressed disliking towards the project, particularly its visuals.<ref name="GRTTb2"/> Hayashi, to his surprise, was ordered to take action and fix it, which led to the conception of ''Valis'' on the spot as Hayashi had an image of a girl fighting with a magical sword.<ref name="GRTTb2"/>

Akishino and Hayashi used the project Ikegame was creating prior to quitting Telenet as a basis to introduce their own story and character ideas.<ref name="GemuShoku"/> Hayashi was responsible for the designs of Yuko and Reiko.<ref name="GemuShoku"/> The idea for ''Valis'' was based on an unfinished personal novel revolving around the light and darkness of the human heart Hayashi wrote prior to development, featuring Yuko and Reiko as main characters.<ref name="GRTTb2"/><ref name="GRTTa1">{{cite web|last=Hayashi|first=Hiroki|url=http://park3.wakwak.com/~garakutaten/novel/novel_top.htm|script-title=ja:図書: - 前書き -|work=我楽多展 - GA・RAKU・TA・TEN|date=2006|access-date=2022-04-09|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060825153601/http://park3.wakwak.com/~garakutaten/novel/novel_top.htm|archive-date=2006-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref> Hayashi used his novel as reference for the game's plot and worldview, which was written in parallel with ''Shoujo Furyou Densetsu''.<ref name="GRTTb2"/> Yamamoto calculated the number of needed tiles for each level early in development, reckoning that using 32x32 sprites would require 1024 tiles for stage maps and began making his own data under this assumption.<ref name="GemuShoku"/> Knowing that the sales team used a program's size and character sprites as marketing ploys, Yamamoto told a Telenet sales staffer that they should be able to scroll large maps.<ref name="GemuShoku"/>

Kouji Yokota served as graphic designer for the [[Family Computer]] version.<ref name="TUHoJGD">{{cite book|last=Szczepaniak|first=John|chapter=横田 幸次 (YOKOTA, Kouji)|title=The Untold History of Japanese Game Developers|date=August 11, 2014|publisher=SMG Szczepaniak|isbn=978-0992926007|pages=574–644}}</ref> Yokota joined Telenet after being introduced to a senior staffer via an acquaintance and applying for a job interview.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/> Yokota particularly cited the story and visual design of ''Valis'' as his reasons to join Telenet.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/> Due to the Family Computer having limited memory compared to home computers and the available [[Memory management controller (Nintendo)|memory mapper chips]] (MMC) being a concern, Yokota implemented a mirroring technique to reuse [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]]s in order to create the graphics.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/> Because the original version featured multi-directional scrolling not possible on the Family Computer, and games on the platform at that time had either vertical or horizontal scrolling, Yokota and the staff were forced to take a different approach.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/> The team added changes and revisions to the game's design, introducing an exploration component and more complex maps to deepen its gameplay.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/> Yokota has since regarded the Family Computer version to be a remake rather than a port.<ref name="TUHoJGD"/>

== Release ==
''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'' was first published for the [[MSX]] in Japan on November 26, 1986, by [[Telenet Japan]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://ia601205.us.archive.org/19/items/MSXMagazine-Japan/MsxMagazine198612.pdf|script-title=ja:メガROMソフト大: 日本テレネット - 夢幻戦士ヴァリス|magazine=[[:ja:MSXマガジン|MSX Magazine]]|issue=38|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=December 1986|page=161|lang=ja}}</ref> It was followed by conversions for the [[PC-8800 series|PC-8801]] and [[X1 (computer)|X1]] computers on December of that year,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/OhMZOhx19861989/Oh%21MZ_1986-12/page/n82/mode/1up|title=The Softouch - Software Information: 夢幻戦士ヴァリス|magazine=[[:ja:Oh!MZ|Oh!MZ]]|issue=56|publisher=[[SoftBank Creative]]|date=December 1986|page=81|lang=ja}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=28152&redirect=no|script-title=ja:夢幻戦士ヴァリス(PC-8801)の関連情報|work=[[Famitsu.com]]|publisher=[[Kadokawa Corporation]]|date=2013|access-date=2022-03-19|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220319212244/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=28152&redirect=no|archive-date=2022-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as for [[FM-7]] and [[PC-9800 series|PC-9801]] computers in 1987.<ref name="ValisHG101"/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Yamashita|first=Akira|url=https://archive.org/details/micomBASIC_1987-02/page/n297/mode/2up|title=BGM・グラフィックス最高！— ヴァリス|magazine=[[:ja:マイコンBASICマガジン|Micom BASIC Magazine]]|issue=56|publisher=[[:ja:電波新聞社|The Dempa Shimbunsha Corporation]]|date=February 1987|pages=272–273|lang=ja}}</ref> These versions were handled by [[Wolf Team]].<ref name="ValisHG101"/> Telenet would later develop an almost completely reworked version of ''Valis'' for the [[Family Computer]], published only in Japan by [[Tokuma Shoten]] on August 21 of the same year.<ref name="ValisHG101"/><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/famimaga-jul-1987/page/174/mode/2up|script-title=ja:夢幻戦士ヴァリス|magazine=[[Tokuma Shoten#Magazines|Family Computer Magazine]]|volume=3|issue=12|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=July 3, 1987|pages=174–175|lang=ja }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter=12 年の歳月で発売された全 1052 本のゲームタイトル！ ファミコンソフ卜褰耋圍編: 1987|title=懐かしファミコンパーフェクトガイド|volume=1|series=Perfect Guide|publisher=Magazine Box|date=April 21, 2016|pages=124|language=ja|isbn=978-4906735891}}</ref> In 1991, a remake of ''Valis'' for the [[Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]] was developed and published in Japan by [[Telenet Japan|Riot]], another game development division of Telenet.<ref name="GSW">{{cite web|last=Ciolek|first=Todd|url=http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2007/12/column_might_have_been_telenet.php|title=Column: 'Might Have Been' - Telenet Japan|work=[[GameSetWatch]]|publisher=[[UBM plc]]|date=December 17, 2007|access-date=2020-07-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071218051721/http://www.gamesetwatch.com/2007/12/column_might_have_been_telenet.php|archive-date=2007-12-18|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://sega.jp/fb/segahard/md/soft_licensee.html|script-title=ja:ソフトウェア一覧（ソフトライセンシー発売）&#124; メガドライブ|encyclopedia=SEGA HARD Encyclopedia|publisher=[[Sega]]|date=2022|access-date=2022-03-19|lang=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200626053415/https://sega.jp/fb/segahard/md/soft_licensee.html|archive-date=2020-06-26|url-status=live}}</ref> This version features character artwork by Osamu Nabeshima.<ref name="GSW"/> Telenet also released the game through its subsidiary [[Renovation Products]] in North America.<ref name="GSW"/><ref name="SegaVisionsSMDv"/> A European release was planned by [[UbiSoft]], as part of a multi-game licensing deal with Renovation, but it was never officially released in the region for unknown reasons.<ref name="MegaT1">{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:MegaTech_UK_01.pdf&page=6|title=News – Ubisoft in exclusive Megadrive Game Import Deal Shocker!|magazine=[[MegaTech]]|issue=1|publisher=[[Ascential|E