The [[PC Engine Super CD-ROM²]] remake of ''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'' received more favorable response from reviewers.<ref name="FamPCESCDROMmsv"/><ref name="GPCEPCESCDROMtloafs"/> It ranked at the number 119 spot with a 22.82 out of 30 score in a public poll taken by ''[[PC Engine Fan]]'' as well.<ref name="PCEFv6i10">{{cite magazine|title=PC Engine All Catalog '93 10月号特別付録 - 夢幻戦士ヴァリス|magazine=[[PC Engine Fan]]|volume=6|issue=10|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=October 1, 1993|page=32|lang=ja}}</ref> Jacques Harbonn of ''Consoles +'' commended the presentation for its animated cutscenes, graphics, Yuko's animations and soundtrack, but criticized the lack of additional gameplay options, underdeveloped backgrounds, and issues with the jumping mechanic for interfering with combat.<ref name="CPPCESCDROMvtloafs"/> ''Génération 4''{{'}}s Philippe Querleux praised the visuals and soundtrack but criticized Yuko's occasionally unresponsive controls and slow movement.<ref name="Gen4PCESCDROMtloafs"/> ''Joystick''{{'}}s Jean-Marc Demoly and ''Joypad'' co-writer Jean-François Morisse gave positive remarks for its audiovisual presentation and controls.<ref name="JPPCESCDROMv"/><ref name="JSPCESCDROMv"/>

In a retrospective outlook, ''[[GameFan]]''{{'}}s Eric L. Patterson found the PC Engine better over the Genesis version, citing its tight controls, enemy designs, varied backgrounds, and redbook audio.<ref name="GameFanv7i4">{{cite magazine|last=Patterson|first=Eric L.|url=https://archive.org/details/Gamefan_Vol_7_Issue_04/page/n77/mode/2up|title=The Graveyard: The Legend Of A Fantasm Soldier Valis|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=7|issue=4|publisher=Shinno Media|date=April 1999|pages=76–77}}</ref> ''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s Lucas M. Thomas placed it as number six among his top ten list of TurboGrafx{{efn|North American version of the PC Engine}} titles not released on the [[Virtual Console]].<ref name="IGN">{{cite web|last=Thomas|first=Lucas M.|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/10/17/retro-remix-top-10-unreleased-turbografx-titles|title=Retro Remix: Top 10 Unreleased TurboGrafx Titles - Our Virtual Console countdown continues, as we take a look at the top ten titles from Hudson's two Turbos|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=17 October 2008|access-date=2022-03-17|archive-date=2022-03-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220308054430/https://www.ign.com/articles/2008/10/17/retro-remix-top-10-unreleased-turbografx-titles|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Retro Gamer]]''{{'}}s Rory Milne highlighted it as "arguably the best" entry in the series.<ref name="RG">{{cite magazine|last=Milne|first=Rory|title=Minority Report: Japanese Warriors|magazine=[[Retro Gamer]]|issue=129|publisher=[[Imagine Publishing]]|date=May 22, 2014|pages=45}}</ref> Derboo from ''Hardcore Gaming 101'' regarded it as the most well-executed game in the series, however he wrote that "It's still a bit too derivative and pedestrian to be counted among the genre greats like ''[[Castlevania]]'' and ''[[Ninja Gaiden]]'', but at least very, very high second tier."<ref name="ValisHG101"/>

== Legacy ==
{{main|Valis (video game series)}}
''Valis: The Fantasm Soldier'' spawned a series of three sequels released during the [[fourth generation of video game consoles]]:  ''[[Valis II]]'' (1989), ''[[Valis III]]'' (1990), and ''[[Valis IV]]'' (1991).<ref name="MSXForce8"/> In addition to the main games, an [[eroge]] [[visual novel]] spin-off titled ''[[Valis X]]'' was developed by Eants and released in 2006 on the 20th anniversary of the series, being the last game published by Telenet Japan. It is divided into five episodes that retell the stories of the first four titles, containing copious amounts of lesbian acts and tentacle erotica.<ref name="GSW"/><ref name="MSXForce8"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Mizuguchi|first=Makoto|url=http://www.inside-games.jp:80/article/2010/04/07/41449.html|title=「死んでいた方がよかったゲーム」－復活したのが間違いだった？|work=Inside Games|publisher=IID, Inc.|date=April 7, 2010|access-date=2022-06-03|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704002244/http://www.inside-games.jp:80/article/2010/04/07/41449.html|archive-date=2010-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kalata|first=Kurt|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/valis-x/|title=Valis X|work=[[Hardcore Gaming 101]]|date=January 29, 2012|access-date=2022-06-03|archive-date=2022-02-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220203142007/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/valis-x/|url-status=live}}</ref> Outside  of video games, a four-volume ''Valis'' manga series by the artist ZOL was published by [[Kill Time Communication]] and featured in the [[seinen manga]] magazine ''[[Comic Valkyrie]]'' between 2007 and 2012.<ref name="RM5"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comic-valkyrie.com/valis/|title=夢幻戦士ヴァリス|work=[[Comic Valkyrie]]|publisher=[[Kill Time Communication]]|date=2012|access-date=2022-06-03|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210614004559/https://www.comic-valkyrie.com/valis/|archive-date=2021-06-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2023, an homage to the series titled ''Violet Wisteria'' was developed by KaniPro Games and released for [[Windows]] (via [[Steam (service)|Steam]]), followed by versions for [[Nintendo Switch]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[PlayStation 5]], [[Xbox One]], and [[Xbox Series X and Series S]] published by [[Eastasiasoft]] in 2024.<ref>{{cite web|last=Davison|first=Pete|url=https://ricedigital.co.uk/violet-wisteria-review/|title=Violet Wisteria is an unabashedly old-school homage to Valis|work=Rice Digital|publisher=Rice Digital Ltd.|date=February 13, 2023|access-date=2023-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230319170829/https://ricedigital.co.uk/violet-wisteria-review/|archive-date=2023-03-19|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hagues|first=Alana|url=https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2024/03/nintendo-download-7th-march-north-america|title=Nintendo Download: 7th March (North America)|work=[[Nintendo Life]]|publisher=[[Hookshot Media]]|date=March 7, 2024|access-date=2024-03-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240307155926/https://www.nintendolife.com/news/2024/03/nintendo-download-7th-march-north-america|archive-date=2024-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="TrueAchivements">{{cite news|last=Carey|first=Sean|url=https://www.trueachievements.com/news/new-xbox-games-march-11|title=New Xbox games — March 11 to 17|work=[[TrueAchievements]]|publisher=TrueGaming Network Ltd|date=March 10, 2024|access-date=2024-03-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240329030652/https://www.trueachievements.com/news/new-xbox-games-march-11|archive-date=2024-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Rebecca|url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2024/03/11/ps5-ps4-new-games-march-11-17-2024-psvr-2/|title=PS5 and PS4 Releases: Every Game Release Date for Week Beginning March 11, 2024|work=[[PlayStation LifeStyle]]|publisher=Evolve Media|date=March 11, 2024|access-date=2024-03-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240311210907/https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2024/03/11/ps5-ps4-new-games-march-11-17-2024-psvr-2